com.camerontec.catalys.server.sessionmanager

Interface ISessionManager

  • All Superinterfaces:
    Cloneable, EventListener, ICatalysEventListener, IComponent, IConfigurable, IEndOfDayPerformer, IFIXMessageProcessor, IHasAttributes, IMessageListener, IMessageProcessor, IMessageSource, IRegisterable
    All Known Implementing Classes:
    SessionManager

    public interface ISessionManager
extends IFIXMessageProcessor
    An object that controls the FIX Session for a given ConnectionPoint.

    A connection point's sessions may come and go but its SessionManager is always present.

    Each session manager is uniquely associated with a connection point.

    A session manager is also the interface between a FIX session and the message processors for that connection point's FIX messages.

    The session manager does not create sessions. It expects to have a fully connected and logged on session passed to it. Its job is to manage a session once it is logged on.

      • connectSession

        void connectSession(boolean connect,
                    String reason)
             throws Exception
        Attempts to connect or disconnect a session.

        If connect is true, this will make every attempt to connect to the session, irrespective of whether a session is normally scheduled for this time or not. However, if the session is blocked (see isBlocked()) an exception is thrown.

        If connect is false, this will try to cleanly terminate the session by sending a logout message. Note that this is a cleaner way to shutdown than dropSession() which just drops any connection.

        Parameters:
        connect - Connect if true, disconnect if false.
        reason - Text explaining reason for connect/disconnect. May be null.
        Throws:
        FatalProtocolException - if we are blocked.
        Exception - TBD

      • dropSession

        void dropSession()
        Terminates any existing session and closes any associated connection.

        Note that this does not send a logout. It just drops the connection. A cleaner way to shutdown a session is to send a logout message which is what connectSession(boolean, java.lang.String) will do when called passing false as a parameter.

      • isOutsideSchedule

        Boolean isOutsideSchedule()
        Returns true if my connection point is outside the normal times when we would expect it to be scheduled to be connected, false if inside schedule and null if we don't know (because no scheduler is active).

        This is determined by looking in the scheduler for the next scheduled start and stop tasks. If the next task to be scheduled is the stop task, then it is assumed that we should currently be connected. If it is the start task, it is assumed that we should not.

        If no scheduler is active, then always returns null.

        Returns:
        True if our connection point is not currently expected to be connected.

      • setBlocked

        void setBlocked(boolean blocked)
        A blocked connection point will never connect.

        A client session will never initiate a connection while blocked.

        A server session will reject any incoming connection attempts while blocked.

        Note that blocking an active session will not automatically disconnect that session - it will just mark it as blocked so that no future connections are made. You should use the connectSession(boolean, java.lang.String) method to connect or disconnect a session.

        Parameters:
        blocked - True if blocked.

      • setLocked

        void setLocked(boolean locked)
        A locked connection point will never connect.

        A client session will never initiate a connection while locked.

        A server session will reject any incoming connection attempts while locked.

        Note that locking an active session will not automatically disconnect that session - it will just mark it as locked so that no future connections are made. You should use the connectSession(boolean, java.lang.String) method to connect or disconnect a session.

        Parameters:
        locked - True if locked.

      • setPendingSession

        void setPendingSession(Session pendingSession)
        Informs SessionManager that we are in the process of trying to log on to the given session.

        The session manager does not take over control of this session at this point - it simply listens to its events so that it can monitor what is going on.

        Once the session has been fully accepted and logged on, control may be passed to the session manager using setSession(com.camerontec.catalys.core.session.Session, com.camerontec.catalys.core.message.IFIXMessage).

        Parameters:
        pendingSession - Session to be monitored.

      • setSession

        void setSession(Session session,
                IFIXMessage message)
        Passes a session to be managed.

        If it is not null, the session should be connected and logged on. The message that identified the session is passed in. Normally this will be a Logon message. However, it may not be if the session was already in a logged on state.

        The session may be null, in which case the manager has no session to manage.

        If the manager is currently managing another session, that session will be terminated abruptly - that is, no Logout message is sent. The session AND its associated connection is simply closed.

        Parameters:
        session - Null or a logged on session.
        message - The other party's message which identified this session. Usually a Logon message. May be null if session is null.

      • setTimerecorder

        void setTimerecorder(IAccumulator timerecorder)
        Associate timing recording with this session.

        The actual timing instrumentation is delegated down to the associated Session object. The recording takes place following the writing of each FIX message out over a FIX connection. The difference between current time and any time stamp on the written message is recorded.

        Parameters:
        timerecorder - object used to accumulate timing data based on message timestamps.

      • getTimerecorder

        Returns:
        the time recorder. Can be null if not set.
        See Also:
        setTimerecorder(IAccumulator)

      • setTimestamping

        void setTimestamping(boolean value)
        If timestamping is enabled, each message read from a FIX connection is immediately timestamped with the current time using System.nanoTime().

        The actual time stamping is delegated down to the MessageAssembler of the associated Session object.

        Parameters:
        value - True to enable time stamping mode, false to disable it (the default).
